1
00:00:00,240 --> 00:00:07,960
Very few people know about the rank function even fewer use it in practice.

2
00:00:07,960 --> 00:00:14,380
This is all the more reason to understand what it does and how it serves you in practice.

3
00:00:14,380 --> 00:00:20,710
It is more than likely that you will face a situation where you will have to rank a company's clients

4
00:00:21,160 --> 00:00:28,430
suppliers employees or water suppliers in a list based on specific criteria.

5
00:00:28,450 --> 00:00:36,370
For example if you are ranking clients you might want to understand which client account drove the highest

6
00:00:36,370 --> 00:00:41,660
gross profit or revenues if you are ranking suppliers.

7
00:00:41,710 --> 00:00:49,140
You might want to find out which supplier invoiced the highest amount and so on and so forth.

8
00:00:49,150 --> 00:00:56,950
Some people would do such a comparison by using custom sort and sorting according to a specific column.

9
00:00:56,950 --> 00:01:03,490
But that's far from ideal because it requires you to change your source data and takes away some of

10
00:01:03,490 --> 00:01:06,780
the flexibility that formulas could give you.

11
00:01:06,790 --> 00:01:09,990
This is where rank function comes into play.

12
00:01:10,060 --> 00:01:13,150
It works in a very straightforward manner.

13
00:01:13,270 --> 00:01:17,390
Its first argument is the number to be rank power case.

14
00:01:17,530 --> 00:01:25,750
This is the first number in this range of cells then the second argument simply consists in the range

15
00:01:25,750 --> 00:01:34,640
of cells to be ranked with respect to I'LL FIX THE RANGE references as I will paste the function downwards

16
00:01:34,880 --> 00:01:39,020
in a moment Okay perfect.

17
00:01:39,120 --> 00:01:46,140
What Excel will do in this situation is go ahead and compare the number we have selected as our first

18
00:01:46,140 --> 00:01:53,340
argument with respect to the rest of the numbers in the range of cells chosen as a second argument.

19
00:01:53,370 --> 00:01:58,010
Simple as that and here's the result.

20
00:01:58,380 --> 00:02:04,980
If I copy and paste the function downwards I'll obtain the rank of each of the cells within the indicated

21
00:02:04,980 --> 00:02:13,070
range what's even neater is that we can then use a v lookup function to transfer this ranking to a different

22
00:02:13,070 --> 00:02:16,310
sheet and all of this would remain dynamic.

23
00:02:17,330 --> 00:02:24,420
Here is a sheet where we have a list of our top 10 client accounts for the latest a month next month.

24
00:02:24,420 --> 00:02:31,470
If the top 10 customers change the ranking in the source sheets would change as well and the list reported

25
00:02:31,470 --> 00:02:36,000
here would update automatically quite nice writes.
